Introduction¶

YouTube is a major platform for movie productions to gain interest in their next film. I personally feel thrilled when I see that a new Marvel Trailer dropped! But how closely does the general opinion of a trailer relate to the overall rating of the movie? Join me below to find out!

We will use YouTube and IMDB API's to scrape movie comments and movie ratings for all of Marvel's movies (excluding Dr. Strange in the Multiverse of Madness since the rating is still fluctuating). Using the movie comments, we will perform a sentiment analysis to see the general feelings the audience had toward the trailer, and we wish to see how this feeling connects to the final performance of the movie.

Finally, we will build a simple ML model to try to predict the movie rating from the average polarity of the movie.

Included in this repository are two scripts that do the heavy lifting of scraping the movie information: ScrapeComments.py and ScrapeIMDB.py. I invite you to look at the scripts if you are curious for how the data was collected.

def create_plots(rows = 1, cols = 1):
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(rows, cols)
    fig.set_size_inches(20,10)
    return fig, axs

def clean_plot(axs, g, title):
    """
    remove ticks, add title, add counts above bars, remove grid lines
    """
    plt.tick_params(left = False, bottom = False , labelbottom = False)
    g.set(ylabel = None, xlabel = None, title = title)
    g.bar_label(g.containers[0], labels = ['{:,.0f}'.format(val) for val in g.containers[0].datavalues])
    axs.grid(False)

plt.tick_params(left = False, labelleft = False)
plt.show()

Data Cleaning¶

From above, we can see the most common word is "the". That's not very helpful, so we will remove the stop words from the dataset.

In order to conserve the meaning of the sentences, we will perform lemmatization using NLTK before removing stopwords in order to capture the correct POS. Since the purpose of this project is to find the sentiment of the comments, we will keep the stopwords in new column of the dataframe but remove them in another.

In [ ]:
class CommentCleaner:
    def __init__(self):
        self.stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english'))
        self.pos_map = defaultdict(lambda: 'n')
        self.pos_map.update({'VB' : 'v',
                            'VBD' : 'v',
                            'VBG' : 'v',
                            'VBN' : 'v',
                            'VBP' : 'v',
                            'VBZ' : 'v',
                            'JJ' : 'a',
                            'JJR' : 'a',
                            'JJS' : 'a',
                            'RB' : 'r',
                            'RBR' : 'r',
                            'RBS' : 'r',
                            'WRB' : 'r'
                            })
    
    def lemmatize_comments(self, comment):
        lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()
        return [lemmatizer.lemmatize(word, self.pos_map[pos]) for (word, pos) in nltk.pos_tag(word_tokenize(comment))]

    def clean_comments(self, comment, remove_stopwords = False):
        # lower case all
        comment = comment.lower()
        # remove hyperlinks
        comment = re.sub(r'^https?:\/\/.*', '', comment)
        # remove punctuations
        comment = comment.translate(str.maketrans('', '', string.punctuation))
        # replace numbers with the word "number"
        comment = re.sub(r'[0-9]+', 'number', comment)
        # lemmatize words
        comment_lemmatized = self.lemmatize_comments(comment)
        if remove_stopwords:
            final = ' '.join([word for word in comment_lemmatized if word not in self.stop_words])
        else:
            final = ' '.join(comment_lemmatized)
        return final

Sentiment Analysis¶

Now we will create two columns from the comment_lemmatized_only feature of our dataset: polarity and subjectivity.

The polarity of a comment defines how positive or negative the comment is. The polarity values range from -1 to + 1; +1 is a high positive polarity and -1 is a high negative polarity. The subjectivity of the comment defines how objective or subjective the comment is. The subjectivity values range from 0 to 1; 0 is an objective comment and 1 is a subjective comment.

In [ ]:
df_comments['comment_subjectivity'] = df_comments['comment_lemmatized_only'].apply(lambda comment: TextBlob(comment).sentiment.subjectivity)
df_comments['comment_polarity'] = df_comments['comment_lemmatized_only'].apply(lambda comment: TextBlob(comment).sentiment.polarity)

def add_label(score):
    if type(score) == str:
        return 'Neutral'
    elif score > 0:
        return 'Positive'
    elif score == 0:
        return 'Neutral'
    else:
        return 'Negative'

df_comments['comment_label'] = df_comments['comment_polarity'].apply(add_label)

Connecting Polarity to Ratings¶

Finally, let's join our data containing the average polarity scores for the movies with the ratings. We'll do a simple scatterplot to see how the two features relate, then we will select a simple ML algorithm to map the polarity to the movie rating.

NOTE : I realize that looking at all movies plotted will introduce some bias to the model I choose. I won't worry too much about that since the dataset only contains 26 movies (which is a really small number of datapoints for an ML project). The purpose of this project is to see how the comments can relate to the movie ratings and I believe we are accomplishing that.

In [ ]:
def jittery():
    return random.uniform(1,1.01)

# function for adding movie name to scatterplot
def label_point(x, y, val, ax):
    a = pd.concat({'x': x, 'y': y, 'val': val}, axis=1)
    for i, point in a.iterrows():
        ax.text(point['x']*1.01, point['y']*jittery(), str(point['val']))

It looks like we have a positive correlation with the polarity of the trailer and the overall rating of the movie. Let's see if we can incorporate the emotion scores into the polarity to see how the plot changes.

We will add the "Happy" and "Surprise" scores to the polarity to see how much the emotion of the comments can influence the final polarity.

Random Forest¶

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor

rmse_train = mean_squared_error(y_true = y_train, y_pred = y_hat, squared = False)
print('The model predicts the movie ratings for the training set within {:.3f} of a rating point, from a scale of 1-10'.format(rmse_train))

The model predicts the movie ratings for the training set within 0.193 of a rating point, from a scale of 1-10

This model performed much better than the Linear Regression model on the test set, however, this is probably highly over-fitting since the training size is so small. Let's see the performance on the test set.

In [ ]:
y_hat_test = rf_fitted.predict(X_test)
rmse_test = mean_squared_error(y_true = y_test, y_pred = y_hat_test, squared = False)
print('The model predicts the movie ratings for the training set within {:.3f} of a rating point, from a scale of 1-10'.format(rmse_test))

The model predicts the movie ratings for the training set within 0.447 of a rating point, from a scale of 1-10

Here we see the model performed worse on the test set than the Linear Regression model. This is expected since the model definitely over-fitted the dataset. We could put some effort into making the model more flexible, but our efforts would be better used in finding more data to train with.

Conclusion¶

From this project, we can see that there is value in extracting information from YouTube trailers for movies. This project can be expanded by including much more data; this dataset contains trailers for 276 of the Marvel movies in the MCU, but does not contain any other YouTube comments from other videos that Marvel publishes. By expanding the scope of the videos chosen to scrape comments for, we can build a better predictor. With the limited data used in this project, we were still able to predict movie ratings within 0.4 rating points. That is the equivalent of someone recommending a movie because they found the movie to be a "8.5" out of "10" while you found it to be an "8" or "9" out of 10 - I would consider that a pretty close score!
